Yeah, I disagree
1) Not clear how likely he is to actually run and 1b) stay the course;
2) Not clear how he gets an appreciable fraction of the vote;
3) Not clear he'd play a spoiler role—contra the CW, he's probably about equally likely to draw from either major party candidate.

There's also pretty strong agreement among the various probabilistic forecasters on odds of a D House majority:

@ORACLE_of_Blair: 75%
@gelliottmorris: 79%
538 Lite / Classic / Deluxe: 80% / 87% / 85%
@TheEconomist: 86%
@YouGovUS: 89%
Optimus/@DecisionDeskHQ: 95%

Dem chances to gain 23+ seats in the various quant House models:

@ORACLE_of_Blair — 76%
@FiveThirtyEight — Lite / Classic / Deluxe — 78% / 85% / 82%
Economist/@gelliottmorris — 86%
Optimus/@DecisionDeskHQ — 95%

So for better or worse, these things are in pretty good consensus.*

Tangible on several levels:
1) Money can be exchanged for goods and services, e.g., ads;
2) It's a good proxy for how well-organized a campaign is;
3) It's a good proxy for voter enthusiasm.

EXPLAINER: People are still tweeting about [redacted] because:
1) Journalists love to argue;
2) It's a proxy war in a huge fight, which is whether journalism's problems are a result of (a) its failure to abide by its traditions, or (b) its adherence to a failed set of traditions.

My guess:
1) There was a pro-Trump faction within the FBI and the Times's sources were heavily weighted toward that faction; 
2) For various reasons having to do with its editorial culture, the Times really leaned into the "Russia overblown" narrative instead of hedging.

If I had to guess, Republicans would take more blame than Democrats. But:
i) Republicans are already so unpopular it might not matter at the margin;
ii) It's January—is this going to be one of the top voting issues in November? Probably not.
